n\\n== All Notes\\n\\n#let notes = yaml(\\\"generated/notes-index.yml\\\")\\n\\n#for note in notes.values() [\\n  - #link(note.path)[#note.title] \\\\\\n    #for tag in note.tags [#raw(\\\"#\\\" + tag) ]\\n]\\n```\\n\\nYou can also generate:\\n\\n```text\\nmain.typ              → full knowledge book\\ntag-typst.typ         → all notes tagged typst\\ndaily-2026-07.typ     → journal/month view\\ngraph.typ             → visual graph page\\nbibliography.typ      → source/reference view\\n```\\n\\n## 8. Tags\\n\\nStore tags in note metadata:\\n\\n```typst\\n#zk-note(\\n  id: \\\"20260702-typst-pkms\\\",\\n  title: \\\"Typst as a PKMS framework\\\",\\n  tags: (\\\"typst\\\", \\\"pkms\\\", \\\"zettelkasten\\\"),\\n)[\\n  ...\\n]\\n```\\n\\nGenerate `tags.yml`:\\n\\n```yaml\\ntypst:\\n  - 20260702-typst-pkms\\n  - 20260702-zettelkasten-links\\n\\npkms:\\n  - 20260702-typst-pkms\\n```\\n\\nThen render tag pages from Typst.\\n\\n## 9. Sources and citations\\n\\nFor serious PKMS/Zettelkasten, sources should be first-class.\\n\\nTypst already has bibliography support and citation syntax. It supports built-in citation styles and custom CSL files. citeturn875371search2turn875371search8\\n\\nExample:\\n\\n```typst\\n#bibliography(\\\"bibliography.yml\\\")\\n\\nAccording to @luhmann1992, note systems become powerful through internal links.\\n```\\n\\nA note can have both:\\n\\n```typst\\nlinks: (\\\"20260702-some-related-note\\\",)\\nsources: (\\\"luhmann1992\\\", \\\"ahrens2017\\\")\\n```\\n\\nMeaning:\\n\\n```text\\nlinks   = relation to your own notes\\nsources = relation to external references\\n```\\n\\nDo not mix them.\\n\\n## 10. Graph\\n\\nGraph should be generated outside Typst.\\n\\nExample `graph.json`:\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"nodes\\\": [\\n    {\\\"id\\\": \\\"20260702-typst-pkms\\\", \\\"title\\\": \\\"Typst as a PKMS framework\\\"},\\n    {\\\"id\\\": \\\"20260702-zettelkasten-links\\\", \\\"title\\\": \\\"Zettelkasten links\\\"}\\n  ],\\n  \\\"edges\\\": [\\n    {\\\"from\\\": \\\"20260702-typst-pkms\\\", \\\"to\\\": \\\"20260702-zettelkasten-links\\\"}\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen either:\\n\\n```text\\ngraph.json → SVG → include in Typst\\n```\\n\\nor:\\n\\n```text\\ngraph.json → web viewer\\n```\\n\\nTypst is good for rendering the graph as a document artifact, but not for interactive graph navigation.\\n\\n## 11. Search\\n\\nSearch is not Typst’s job.\\n\\nClean options:\\n\\n```text\\nSimple version:\\n  ripgrep over .typ files\\n\\nBetter version:\\n  SQLite FTS5 index\\n\\nAdvanced version:\\n  vector embeddings + semantic search\\n```\\n\\nTypst remains the source format and renderer. Search index is generated from Typst notes.\\n\\n## 12. What “full support” means here\\n\\nFor Typst-based Zettelkasten/PKMS, “full support” would mean:\\n\\n| Feature | Implementation |\\n|---|---|\\n| Atomic notes | One `.typ` file per note |\\n| Stable note IDs | Filename + `id` metadata |\\n| Wiki-like links | `#zlink(\\\"note-id\\\")[text]` |\\n| Backlinks | Generated `backlinks.yml` |\\n| Tags | Note metadata + generated tag pages |\\n| Aliases | Note metadata + generated alias map |\\n| Graph | Generated `graph.json` / SVG |\\n| Search | External index |\\n| Citations | Typst bibliography |\\n| Attachments | `assets/` folder + Typst links/includes |\\n| Export | Typst compile to PDF/HTML/web output |\\n| Long-form writing | Compose notes into larger Typst documents |\\n| Local-first | Plain files + generated indexes |\\n| Git-friendly | Text files, deterministic generated files |\\n\\n## 13. Important limitation\\n\\nTypst is excellent as a **structured publishing and writing layer**. It is not, by itself, a complete interactive PKMS runtime.\\n\\nSo the correct architecture is:\\n\\n```text\\nTypst = note format + rendering + citations + structured metadata\\nScript = indexer + backlink builder + graph builder + search builder\\nUI/editor = optional, separate layer\\n```\\n\\nThis keeps the system clean: Typst files stay readable, printable, versionable, and not locked into a hidden app database.\",\n      \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:55:22.224Z\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"b0d95e72-d485-471a-922b-230109688ac7\",\n      \"role\": \"user\",\n      \"content\": \"if add File tagging and tag management?\",\n      \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:57:59.681Z\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"8d004eef-34ab-40ee-a2e3-59fc082b3f3d\",\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": \"Да. Тогда надо разделить **tags for notes** и **tags for files/assets**. Это разные сущности, иначе быстро получится грязная смесь “тем”, “типов файлов” и “статусов”.\",\n      \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:58:00.851Z\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"590404d0-5aa0-49f9-beb1-c9c03cb6755a\",\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": \"{\\\"system1_search_query\\\":[{\\\"q\\\":\\\"site:typst.app/docs Typst metadata query data loading yaml json official docs\\\"},{\\\"q\\\":\\\"site:typst.app/docs Typst link function bibliography metadata official docs\\\"}],\\\"response_length\\\":\\\"short\\\"}\",\n      \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:58:00.851Z\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"75c1b217-919b-4462-be2d-3b4a1eca5e68\",\n      \"role\": \"tool\",\n      \"content\": \"Displaying results for similar queries\\nThe following search queries were not executed exactly as provided and might also contain outdated information: \\\"site:typst.app/docs typst link function bibliography metadata official docs\\\", \\\"site:typst.app/docs typst metadata query data loading yaml json official docs\\\"\\n\\nPlease retry the search (only) if results are not relevant or stale\",\n      \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:58:12.720Z\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"d9890e12-15c7-4254-ae35-8cd94d2ecff7\",\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n\n[Output truncated. Use view_range=[93, ...] to continue reading. In your next response, you may batch this with other view calls. File has at least 97 lines.]",
  "detailedContent": "\ndiff --git a/Users/berloga/Documents/GitHub/TypstSeq/.ref/zettelkasten-pkms-support_20260702_1158.json b/Users/berloga/Documents/GitHub/TypstSeq/.ref/zettelkasten-pkms-support_20260702_1158.json\nindex 0000000..0000000 100644\n--- a/Users/berloga/Documents/GitHub/TypstSeq/.ref/zettelkasten-pkms-support_20260702_1158.json\n+++ b/Users/berloga/Documents/GitHub/TypstSeq/.ref/zettelkasten-pkms-support_20260702_1158.json\n@@ -1,220 +1,220 @@\n {\n   \"id\": \"6a464297-71fc-83ed-bd02-d1331ecd7092\",\n   \"title\": \"Zettelkasten PKMS support\",\n   \"lastUpdated\": \"2026-07-02T10:58:59.506Z\",\n   \"messages\": [\n     {\n       \"id\": \"e98bd5aa-f50d-40ed-a976-27d539775d91\",\n       \"role\": \"user\",\n       \"content\": \"Full Zettelkasten/PKMS support what is this\",\n       \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:51:06.860Z\"\n     },\n     {\n       \"id\": \"25c037bf-ed51-4e56-ae7b-a2b8057bcbbe\",\n       \"role\": \"assistant\",\n       \"content\": \"**Full Zettelkasten / PKMS support** means the app is not just a notes app. It supports building a long-term knowledge system.\\n\\n**Zettelkasten** = a method for storing small connected ideas.\\n\\nCore idea:\\n\\n> one note = one idea  \\n> every note can link to other notes  \\n> knowledge grows as a network, not as folders only\\n\\nExample:\\n\\n```md\\n# Why rehearsals fail\\n\\nBands often fail rehearsals because the song list, tempo, key, and structure are not agreed before the session.\\n\\nLinks:\\n- [[Rehearsal planning]]\\n- [[Setlist preparation]]\\n- [[Band communication]]\\n```\\n\\n**PKMS** = Personal Knowledge Management System.\\n\\nIt means a system for collecting, organizing, connecting, and reusing your knowledge: notes, documents, ideas, projects, research, tasks, references.\\n\\nWhen an app says **“Full Zettelkasten/PKMS support”**, it usually means it has:\\n\\n| Feature | Meaning |\\n|---|---|\\n| Markdown notes | Notes stored in plain text, not locked format |\\n| Wiki-links | `[[Some Note]]` links between notes |\\n| Backlinks | See which notes link to current note |\\n| Tags | `#music`, `#rag`, `#flowgroove` |\\n| Graph view | Visual map of connected notes |\\n| Daily notes / journal | Notes organized by day |\\n| Search | Fast full-text search |\\n| Folders or namespaces | Optional structure |\\n| Templates | Reusable note formats |\\n| Block references | Link to a paragraph/block, not only whole note |\\n| Attachments | Images, PDFs, audio, files |\\n| Sync | Work across devices |\\n| Export | Markdown, PDF, HTML, etc. |\\n| Local-first option | Your notes can live on your disk/Git |\\n\\nBut **“full support” is often marketing**. For me, real full support means at least:\\n\\n1. **Plain Markdown files**\\n2. **Wiki-links `[[note]]`**\\n3. **Backlinks**\\n4. **Fast search**\\n5. **Tags**\\n6. **Stable export**\\n7. **No lock-in**\\n8. **Good local workflow**\\n9. **Can work with Git**\\n10. **Can scale to thousands of notes**\\n\\nFor your context:  \\n**Obsidian, Logseq, Zettlr, Foam, Dendron, SilverBullet, SiYuan, Trilium** are PKMS/Zettelkasten-like tools. But they support the idea differently.\\n\\nVery rough distinction:\\n\\n| App | More like |\\n|---|---|\\n| Obsidian | Markdown vault + plugins |\\n| Logseq | Outliner + daily journal + block links |\\n| Zettlr | Academic Markdown writing |\\n| Foam | VS Code/Zed-style Markdown wiki |\\n| Dendron | Structured developer wiki |\\n| SilverBullet | Programmable local-first wiki |\\n| SiYuan | Full PKMS, but less plain-Markdown-native |\\n| Trilium | Personal database/wiki, not pure Markdown |\\n\\nFor your GitHub Wiki/local workflow, the most important part is **Markdown + wiki-links + backlinks + Git-friendly files**.  \\nGraph view is nice, but not essential.\",\n       \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:51:07.968Z\"\n     },\n     {\n       \"id\": \"35f24193-23e5-4abd-a737-0c2673eb09ba\",\n       \"role\": \"user\",\n       \"content\": \"stop talking about other apps ! its separate question!\\nhow its possible to implement Full Zettelkasten / PKMS support with Typst framework?\",\n       \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:55:06.662Z\"\n     },\n     {\n       \"id\": \"63802b44-38d1-4082-be76-a77847966264\",\n       \"role\": \"assistant\",\n       \"content\": \"Понял. Отвечаю только про Typst: как из него сделать основу PKMS/Zettelkasten, без сравнения с другими приложениями.\",\n       \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:55:07.818Z\"\n     },\n     {\n       \"id\": \"b2f1ad3d-73af-487d-9995-3bb36f60fe43\",\n       \"role\": \"assistant\",\n       \"content\": \"{\\\"system1_search_query\\\":[{\\\"q\\\":\\\"Typst documentation bibliography labels references link function query selector locate official\\\"},{\\\"q\\\":\\\"Typst package documentation official references bibliography cite labels outline query state metadata\\\"},{\\\"q\\\":\\\"Typst GitHub documentation typst markup labels links references official\\\"}],\\\"response_length\\\":\\\"short\\\"}\",\n       \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:55:07.818Z\"\n     },\n     {\n       \"id\": \"a5174802-5bf9-42cc-8fc9-785acb07433b\",\n       \"role\": \"tool\",\n       \"content\": \"Displaying results for similar queries\\nThe following search queries were not executed exactly as provided and might also contain outdated information: \\\"typst github documentation typst markup labels links references official\\\", \\\"typst package documentation official references bibliography cite labels outline query state metadata\\\"\\n\\nPlease retry the search (only) if results are not relevant or stale\",\n       \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:55:13.526Z\"\n     },\n     {\n       \"id\": \"5cab8f4f-e2df-427d-973e-681f48b78c09\",\n       \"role\": \"assistant\",\n       \"content\": \"{\\\"system1_search_query\\\":[{\\\"q\\\":\\\"Typst CLI query command metadata official docs\\\"},{\\\"q\\\":\\\"Typst CLI watch compile query JSON official docs\\\"}],\\\"response_length\\\":\\\"short\\\"}\",\n       \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:55:13.577Z\"\n     },\n     {\n       \"id\": \"b097a48c-7c9d-4573-9f32-93dcea85b022\",\n       \"role\": \"assistant\",\n       \"content\": \"{\\\"system1_search_query\\\":[{\\\"q\\\":\\\"Typst YAML TOML data loading official docs\\\"},{\\\"q\\\":\\\"Typst import include sys inputs official docs\\\"}],\\\"response_length\\\":\\\"short\\\"}\",\n       \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:55:16.856Z\"\n     },\n     {\n       \"id\": \"93bb732c-ceb0-49e8-94b3-5987cf82b663\",\n       \"role\": \"assistant\",\n       \"content\": \"Главное ограничение: Typst может быть **форматом заметок + компилятором представлений**, но не должен быть единственным “движком базы знаний”. Индекс, поиск, граф и backlinks лучше собирать внешним маленьким скриптом.\",\n       \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:55:22.224Z\"\n     },\n     {\n       \"id\": \"d2df20fd-518f-4e12-9f75-b82ed374635e\",\n       \"role\": \"assistant\",\n       \"content\": \"Yes, it is possible — but **Typst should be the document/knowledge format and rendering layer**, not the whole PKMS engine.\\n\\nA clean implementation looks like this:\\n\\n```text\\nTypst files        = notes and publishable documents\\nTypst macros       = note schema, links, tags, citations\\nTypst metadata     = machine-readable note data\\nExternal script    = index, backlinks, graph, search database\\nTypst export       = PDF / HTML / static site / printable book\\n```\\n\\nTypst already has the important primitives: labels/references, links, metadata exposed to the query system, data loading from JSON/YAML/TOML, bibliography/citations, and scripting. The official docs describe `metadata` as invisible structured data that can be queried, `query` as a way to find labelled elements, and Typst data loading supports JSON/YAML/TOML files. citeturn281944search0turn281944search1turn427283search0\\n\\n## 1. Basic vault structure\\n\\n```text\\npkms/\\n  main.typ\\n  pkms.typ\\n\\n  notes/\\n    20260702-typst-pkms.typ\\n    20260702-zettelkasten-links.typ\\n    20260702-local-first-notes.typ\\n\\n  generated/\\n    notes-index.yml\\n    backlinks.yml\\n    graph.json\\n    tags.yml\\n\\n  assets/\\n    images/\\n    audio/\\n    pdf/\\n\\n  bibliography.yml\\n```\\n\\nThe important rule: **every note is a real Typst file**. No hidden database as the source of truth.\\n\\n## 2. Note format\\n\\nExample note:\\n\\n```typst\\n#import \\\"../pkms.typ\\\": zk-note, zlink, backlinks, tag-list\\n\\n#zk-note(\\n  id: \\\"20260702-typst-pkms\\\",\\n  title: \\\"Typst as a PKMS framework\\\",\\n  tags: (\\\"typst\\\", \\\"pkms\\\", \\\"zettelkasten\\\"),\\n  links: (\\n    \\\"20260702-zettelkasten-links\\\",\\n    \\\"20260702-local-first-notes\\\",\\n  ),\\n  aliases: (\\\"typst-pkms\\\", \\\"typst-zettelkasten\\\"),\\n)[\\n  Typst can work as a structured knowledge-writing format.\\n\\n  The core idea is not to make Typst a database. The core idea is to make\\n  every note explicit, typed, linkable, printable, and exportable.\\n\\n  Related:\\n  - #zlink(\\\"20260702-zettelkasten-links\\\")[Zettelkasten links]\\n  - #zlink(\\\"20260702-local-first-notes\\\")[Local-first notes]\\n\\n  #backlinks(\\\"20260702-typst-pkms\\\")\\n]\\n```\\n\\n## 3. Core Typst macro\\n\\nIn `pkms.typ`:\\n\\n```typst\\n#let zk-note(\\n  id,\\n  title,\\n  tags: (),\\n  links: (),\\n  aliases: (),\\n  body,\\n) = [\\n  #metadata((\\n    kind: \\\"note\\\",\\n    id: id,\\n    title: title,\\n    tags: tags,\\n    links: links,\\n    aliases: aliases,\\n  )) <zk-note>\\n\\n  = #title\\n\\n  #body\\n]\\n```\\n\\nThis is the key move: each note renders normally, but also emits structured metadata. Typst’s `metadata` is specifically meant for exposing arbitrary values to the introspection/query system without visible output. citeturn281944search0\\n\\n## 4. Links between notes\\n\\nTypst has native links and references, but for a PKMS you probably want your own wrapper:\\n\\n```typst\\n#let notes = yaml(\\\"generated/notes-index.yml\\\")\\n\\n#let zlink(id, body) = {\\n  let note = notes.at(id, default: none)\\n\\n  if note == none {\\n    strong(\\\"[missing note: \\\" + id + \\\"]\\\")\\n  } else {\\n    link(note.path)[body]\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen inside a note:\\n\\n```typst\\n#zlink(\\\"20260702-zettelkasten-links\\\")[Zettelkasten links]\\n```\\n\\nThis gives you wiki-link-like behaviour, but in a controlled Typst way. Typst’s `link` function supports links to documents/assets and labels, and bundle export can preserve linking across documents. citeturn875371search6\\n\\n## 5. Backlinks\\n\\nBacklinks should **not** be manually written. They should be generated.\\n\\nFlow:\\n\\n```text\\nnotes/*.typ\\n   ↓\\nextract metadata / parse links\\n   ↓\\ngenerated/backlinks.yml\\n   ↓\\nTypst reads backlinks.yml\\n   ↓\\n#backlinks(current-id)\\n```\\n\\nExample `generated/backlinks.yml`:\\n\\n```yaml\\n20260702-typst-pkms:\\n  - id: 20260702-local-first-notes\\n    title: Local-first notes\\n    path: notes/20260702-local-first-notes.typ\\n  - id: 20260702-zettelkasten-links\\n    title: Zettelkasten links\\n    path: notes/20260702-zettelkasten-links.typ\\n```\\n\\nTypst macro:\\n\\n```typst\\n#let all-backlinks = yaml(\\\"generated/backlinks.yml\\\")\\n\\n#let backlinks(id) = {\\n  let items = all-backlinks.at(id, default: ())\\n\\n  if items.len() > 0 [\\n    == Backlinks\\n\\n    #for item in items [\\n      - #link(item.path)[#item.title]\\n    ]\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\\n\\nTypst can load YAML/JSON/TOML as structured data, so generated indexes are a natural fit. citeturn427283search0turn427283search4\\n\\n## 6. Index generation script\\n\\nTypst itself should not scan your whole filesystem and maintain a database. Use a small external script.\\n\\nMinimal responsibilities:\\n\\n```text\\n1. Find notes/*.typ\\n2. Extract note metadata:\\n   - id\\n   - title\\n   - tags\\n   - aliases\\n   - outgoing links\\n3. Generate:\\n   - notes-index.yml\\n   - backlinks.yml\\n   - tags.yml\\n   - graph.json\\n4. Optionally build search index:\\n   - SQLite FTS5\\n   - Tantivy\\n   - simple JSON index\\n```\\n\\nYou can also use `typst query` around metadata. Typst’s query system can retrieve labelled metadata from the document, and the docs explicitly mention command-line queries for metadata. citeturn281944search0turn281944search1\\n\\n## 7. Global index document\\n\\n`main.typ` can compile the whole vault:\\n\\n```typst\\n#import \\\"pkms.typ\\\": *\\n\\n= Knowledge Base\\n\\n== All Notes\\n\\n#let notes = yaml(\\\"generated/notes-index.yml\\\")\\n\\n#for note in notes.values() [\\n  - #link(note.path)[#note.title] \\\\\\n    #for tag in note.tags [#raw(\\\"#\\\" + tag) ]\\n]\\n```\\n\\nYou can also generate:\\n\\n```text\\nmain.typ              → full knowledge book\\ntag-typst.typ         → all notes tagged typst\\ndaily-2026-07.typ     → journal/month view\\ngraph.typ             → visual graph page\\nbibliography.typ      → source/reference view\\n```\\n\\n## 8. Tags\\n\\nStore tags in note metadata:\\n\\n```typst\\n#zk-note(\\n  id: \\\"20260702-typst-pkms\\\",\\n  title: \\\"Typst as a PKMS framework\\\",\\n  tags: (\\\"typst\\\", \\\"pkms\\\", \\\"zettelkasten\\\"),\\n)[\\n  ...\\n]\\n```\\n\\nGenerate `tags.yml`:\\n\\n```yaml\\ntypst:\\n  - 20260702-typst-pkms\\n  - 20260702-zettelkasten-links\\n\\npkms:\\n  - 20260702-typst-pkms\\n```\\n\\nThen render tag pages from Typst.\\n\\n## 9. Sources and citations\\n\\nFor serious PKMS/Zettelkasten, sources should be first-class.\\n\\nTypst already has bibliography support and citation syntax. It supports built-in citation styles and custom CSL files. citeturn875371search2turn875371search8\\n\\nExample:\\n\\n```typst\\n#bibliography(\\\"bibliography.yml\\\")\\n\\nAccording to @luhmann1992, note systems become powerful through internal links.\\n```\\n\\nA note can have both:\\n\\n```typst\\nlinks: (\\\"20260702-some-related-note\\\",)\\nsources: (\\\"luhmann1992\\\", \\\"ahrens2017\\\")\\n```\\n\\nMeaning:\\n\\n```text\\nlinks   = relation to your own notes\\nsources = relation to external references\\n```\\n\\nDo not mix them.\\n\\n## 10. Graph\\n\\nGraph should be generated outside Typst.\\n\\nExample `graph.json`:\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"nodes\\\": [\\n    {\\\"id\\\": \\\"20260702-typst-pkms\\\", \\\"title\\\": \\\"Typst as a PKMS framework\\\"},\\n    {\\\"id\\\": \\\"20260702-zettelkasten-links\\\", \\\"title\\\": \\\"Zettelkasten links\\\"}\\n  ],\\n  \\\"edges\\\": [\\n    {\\\"from\\\": \\\"20260702-typst-pkms\\\", \\\"to\\\": \\\"20260702-zettelkasten-links\\\"}\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen either:\\n\\n```text\\ngraph.json → SVG → include in Typst\\n```\\n\\nor:\\n\\n```text\\ngraph.json → web viewer\\n```\\n\\nTypst is good for rendering the graph as a document artifact, but not for interactive graph navigation.\\n\\n## 11. Search\\n\\nSearch is not Typst’s job.\\n\\nClean options:\\n\\n```text\\nSimple version:\\n  ripgrep over .typ files\\n\\nBetter version:\\n  SQLite FTS5 index\\n\\nAdvanced version:\\n  vector embeddings + semantic search\\n```\\n\\nTypst remains the source format and renderer. Search index is generated from Typst notes.\\n\\n## 12. What “full support” means here\\n\\nFor Typst-based Zettelkasten/PKMS, “full support” would mean:\\n\\n| Feature | Implementation |\\n|---|---|\\n| Atomic notes | One `.typ` file per note |\\n| Stable note IDs | Filename + `id` metadata |\\n| Wiki-like links | `#zlink(\\\"note-id\\\")[text]` |\\n| Backlinks | Generated `backlinks.yml` |\\n| Tags | Note metadata + generated tag pages |\\n| Aliases | Note metadata + generated alias map |\\n| Graph | Generated `graph.json` / SVG |\\n| Search | External index |\\n| Citations | Typst bibliography |\\n| Attachments | `assets/` folder + Typst links/includes |\\n| Export | Typst compile to PDF/HTML/web output |\\n| Long-form writing | Compose notes into larger Typst documents |\\n| Local-first | Plain files + generated indexes |\\n| G