er tag:\\n\\n```text\\ngenerated/tag-pages/audio-recorder.typ\\ngenerated/tag-pages/manual.typ\\ngenerated/tag-pages/cajon.typ\\n```\\n\\nOr one big index:\\n\\n```typst\\n= Tag Index\\n\\n#import \\\"../pkms.typ\\\": tag-page\\n\\n#tag-page(\\\"audio-recorder\\\")\\n#tag-page(\\\"manual\\\")\\n#tag-page(\\\"cajon\\\")\\n```\\n\\nMacro:\\n\\n```typst\\n#let tag_index = yaml(\\\"generated/tag-index.yml\\\")\\n\\n#let tag-page(tag) = {\\n  let items = tag_index.at(tag, default: ())\\n\\n  [\\n    == #tag\\n\\n    === Notes\\n    #for note in items.notes [\\n      - #link(note.path)[#note.title]\\n    ]\\n\\n    === Files\\n    #for file in items.files [\\n      - #link(file.path)[#file.title] — #file.kind\\n    ]\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\\n\\n## 8. Tag management commands\\n\\nThis should be handled by an external script, not manually by Typst.\\n\\nExample command set:\\n\\n```bash\\npkms tag list\\npkms tag create audio-recorder --type topic\\npkms tag rename recorder audio-recorder\\npkms tag merge field-recorder audio-recorder\\npkms tag add-file zoom-h1e-manual manual gear audio-recorder\\npkms tag remove-file zoom-h1e-manual draft\\npkms tag add-note 20260702-live-monitoring monitoring gear\\npkms validate\\npkms index\\n```\\n\\nMinimum validations:\\n\\n```text\\nunknown tags\\nduplicate aliases\\norphan files\\nmissing files\\nfiles with no tags\\nnotes with no tags\\ntags with no usage\\nbroken file links\\nbroken note links\\ncase duplicates: Audio / audio\\nseparator duplicates: audio-recorder / audio_recorder\\n```\\n\\n## 9. Better schema: do not only use tags\\n\\nFor files, some things should be fields, not tags.\\n\\nBad:\\n\\n```yaml\\ntags:\\n  - pdf\\n  - official\\n  - archived\\n  - portuguese\\n  - 2026\\n```\\n\\nBetter:\\n\\n```yaml\\nkind: pdf\\nsource: official\\nstatus: archived\\nlanguage: pt\\nyear: 2026\\ntags:\\n  - audio-recorder\\n  - manual\\n  - gear\\n```\\n\\nTags should describe meaning and relation. Metadata fields should describe factual properties.\\n\\n## 10. Full architecture\\n\\n```text\\n.typ notes\\n  contain:\\n    - note id\\n    - title\\n    - note tags\\n    - links to other notes\\n    - referenced file ids\\n\\nfiles.yml\\n  contains:\\n    - file ids\\n    - paths\\n    - titles\\n    - file tags\\n    - file metadata\\n\\ntags.yml\\n  contains:\\n    - canonical tags\\n    - aliases\\n    - tag types\\n    - descriptions\\n\\nindexer script\\n  generates:\\n    - note index\\n    - file index\\n    - backlinks\\n    - tag index\\n    - graph\\n    - validation report\\n\\nTypst\\n  renders:\\n    - notes\\n    - file cards\\n    - tag pages\\n    - indexes\\n    - reports\\n    - PDF / HTML / static output\\n```\\n\\n## My critical recommendation\\n\\nFor “full PKMS” with Typst, implement **three registries**:\\n\\n```text\\nnotes are source files\\nfiles are managed assets\\ntags are controlled vocabulary\\n```\\n\\nSo:\\n\\n```text\\nnotes/*.typ              = knowledge\\nregistry/files.yml       = file database\\nregistry/tags.yml        = tag authority\\ngenerated/*.yml          = computed indexes\\n```\\n\\nThis gives you real file tagging and tag management without turning Typst into a messy pseudo-database. Typst stays clean: structured writing, rendering, links, citations, and generated views. The external script does the stateful work.\",\n       \"timestamp\": \"2026-07-02T10:58:12.810Z\"\n     }\n   ]\n }\n"
