# Android Near-Realtime Sync Troubleshooting

## Overview

TyLog currently does file-based WebDAV sync. On Android this is **near-realtime only while the app is active and sync is triggered**; it is not live collaborative editing.

## Symptoms

1. Remote edits do not appear quickly unless user presses **Sync**.
2. Local edits appear uploaded, but another client still sees stale content.
3. Changes from two devices override each other unexpectedly.
4. Sync appears idle after app background/foreground transitions.

## Why this happens now

1. Sync is not a continuous pull loop while app sits idle.
2. Lifecycle transitions (pause/resume) are not yet explicit sync checkpoints.
3. Decision logic uses remote `getlastmodified` vs local file mtime, which is sensitive to skew/granularity.
4. There is no persisted ETag/hash cursor and no full conflict workflow yet.
5. Android background limits can suspend network work unexpectedly.

## Quick repro checklist

1. Open TyLog on Android and one desktop client against same Nextcloud vault.
2. Edit `pages/Test.typ` on desktop, save, wait 30+ seconds.
3. Keep Android app open without manual sync.
4. Observe whether Android note updates automatically.
5. Edit same note on Android before manual sync, then sync on both devices.
6. Check for stale content or conflict copies.

## Safe recovery runbook

1. In TyLog, run **Sync** manually.
2. Run **Rebuild index**.
3. If note still stale, close/reopen app and sync again.
4. Check Nextcloud for conflict copies; never auto-delete them.
5. Resolve conflicts manually in plain `.typ` files and sync again.

## Data to capture for bug reports

1. App version.
2. Device model + Android version.
3. Approximate timestamps for each edit and sync attempt.
4. File path(s) involved.
5. Whether app was foreground/background at each step.
6. Whether Nextcloud generated conflict-copy files.

## Planned work

